erful techniques in action. The result is an enlightening and entertaining practical introduction to the secrets of persuasive speaking and writing—including strategies that are just as effective in today’s offices, schools, courts, and political debates as they were in the Roman forum.How to Win an Argument addresses proof based on rational argumentation, character, and emotion; the parts of a speech; the plain, middle, and grand styles; how to persuade no matter what audience or circumstances you face; and more. Cicero’s words are presented in lively translations, with illuminating introductions; the book also features a brief biography of Cicero, a glossary, suggestions for further reading, and an appendix of the original Latin texts.Astonishingly relevant, this unique anthology of Cicero’s rhetorical and oratorical wisdom will be enjoyed by anyone who ever needs to win arguments and influence people—in other words, all of us.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aPersuasion (Rhetoric). 0aRhetoric, Ancient. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  a44 BC.  a45 BC.  a57 BC.  a58 BC.  a62 BC.  a63 BC.  a80 BC.  a80s BC.  aAdage.  aAnalogy.  aAppius Claudius Caecus.  aArchias.  aAssassination of Julius Caesar.  aAtreus.  aCatiline Orations.  aCatiline.  aCato the Younger.  aCicero.  aClodia.  aClytemnestra.  aConsideration.  aDe Inventione.  aDe Legibus.  aDe Officiis.  aDe Oratore.  aDeductive reasoning.  aDemosthenes.  aDigression.  aEffectiveness.  aElocutio.  aEloquence.  aEnnius.  aEnthymeme.  aEthos.  aEtruria.  aExordium (rhetoric).  aFigure of speech.  aFirst Triumvirate.  aGaius Marius.  aGaius Rabirius (senator).  aGnaeus (praenomen).  aGrand style (rhetoric).  aGrattius.  aGreat power.  aHandbook.